":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Molesey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish <b>Molewski</b> or of its variant   Moleski  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moleski","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish <b>Molewski</b>, unexplained. The surname <i>Moleski</i> is also found in Poland, where it is very rare. Compare   Molesky  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Polish   Molski  ."]}]},{"name":"Sampson","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":65,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":90,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sampson de Molesey II was born about 1225, in East Molesey, Surrey, England, his father, Sampson de Molesey I, was 31 and his mother, Mrs Sampson de Molesey I, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Sampson De Molesey II."},"et":{"about 1225–":"umbes 1225–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1195–1231":"1195–1231","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","East Molesey, Kingston, Surrey, England":"East Molesey, Surrey, England"},"fi":{"about 1225–":"noin 1225–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1195–1231":"1195–1231","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1259